}{\plain \fs24 \b I. Affirmative\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b A. Framework\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b 1. AT {\u8220\'93}One just use{\u8221\'94} burden.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (1) Almost any broad normative claim will be true in some cases and false in others. \softline
Thus, burdening the aff to argue every single instance of the topic destroys debate since it frames \softline
topics in a way that makes them indisputably false. This is the biggest possible impact to any \softline
theory standard since the potential for debate is prerequisite for all other goals of the activity.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (2) His/her interpretation of burdens destroys AC strategy, since I can{\u8217\'92}t know what cases \softline
of eminent domain the NC will defend and I can{\u8217\'92}t cover even a small fraction of all eminent \softline
domain cases in a six-minute AC. That destroys fairness since it steals almost half my speech \softline
time. Fairness is a voter since debate{\u8217\'92}s a game and no one wants to play a game that{\u8217\'92}s rigged.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (3) His/her framework destroys fairness on another level since it explodes research \softline
burdens by forcing me to research every single taking in history to prepare for the round if I want \softline
good answers in the 1AR. Since this research burden is impossible, it prevents me from \softline
preparing for round. It also destroys education since it negates any incentive to do affirmative \softline
research or to research more general topic literature. Learning is a voter since it{\u8217\'92}s the goal of \softline
debate and the reason schools fund it.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab You can sign your ballot on this abuse for two reasons: (a) Voting here discourages other \softline
debaters from using arguments that harm learning and fairness in future. (b) Since his/her \softline
framework precludes debate, it skews my time and deprives us of topic learning my forcing me to \softline
run theory in the 1AR rather than talking about arguments.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (4) To win that the example of eminent domain s/he gives you in the NC is just, s/he has \softline
to show that it doesn{\u8217\'92}t bite into the general problems with takings discussed in the AC. Unless \softline
s/he shows why each my arguments don{\u8217\'92}t apply to the case s/he presents, that case is still unjust \softline
and you affirm.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
