}{\plain \fs24 \b 2. AT {\u8220\'93}Eminent domain neither just nor unjust{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab All the arguments in the NC claiming that eminent domain is neither just nor unjust are \softline
on-face reasons to affirm. The neg is burdened to show that eminent domain is just for two \softline
reasons: First, the prefix {\u8220\'93}un{\u8221\'94} implies negation, so {\u8220\'93}X is not just{\u8221\'94} is semantically equivalent to \softline
{\u8220\'93}X is unjust{\u8221\'94}. Second, fair division of ground requires that the neg advocate the converse of the \softline
resolution. If I have to say that eminent domain is unjust but s/he can say that it{\u8217\'92}s either just or \softline
neither, s/he has twice my ground for research and argumentation, exacerbating the neg{\u8217\'92}s \softline
structural advantage based on speech times. Since debate{\u8217\'92}s a game, fairness is a constraint.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Since s/he concedes in the NC that eminent domain{\u8217\'92}s not just, you affirm on face. This \softline
functions as a straight turn on [identify arguments claiming that eminent domain is neither just \softline
nor unjust] and a takeout on the rest of his/her offense since s/he can{\u8217\'92}t argue that eminent domain \softline
is just when s/he{\u8217\'92}s already conceded that it{\u8217\'92}s not.\par
