}{\plain \fs24 \b C. Meta-ethics\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b 1. AT Alasdair MacIntyre\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (1) MacIntyre{\u8217\'92}s argument isn{\u8217\'92}t unique to normative claims. If all chains of reasoning are \softline
finite and terminate in unprovable assertions, then no more possible to prove positive claims \softline
objectively than normative ones. The impacts are that: (a) If you buy MacIntyre, you can never \softline
negate since you can never have solid grounds for believing that propositions like {\u8220\'93}The neg won \softline
the round{\u8221\'94} or {\u8220\'93}I should negate{\u8221\'94} are true; (b) You can{\u8217\'92}t buy MacIntyre, since his own argument \softline
terminates in assertions, for instance the assertion that all chains of reasoning must be finite, so \softline
by his own logic you have no grounds for buying his conclusion.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (2) We accept arguments ending in assertions all the time if those assertions are self-evident. For instance, I don{\u8217\'92}t think the sky is blue because it{\u8217\'92}s logically entailed by a set of \softline
premises I accept{\u8211\'96}I believe it because when I look outside, the sky is self-evidently blue. Thus, \softline
basing arguments on terminal assertions doesn{\u8217\'92}t make those arguments invalid.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (3) The impact of MacIntyre is just that logically complete proofs of normative claims are \softline
impossible. But my burden in the round isn{\u8217\'92}t to prove eminent domain unjust from a set of \softline
ontological axioms, since it would be impossible to do that in six minutes. The only way be can \softline
debate real-world topics within a reasonable timeframe is by appealing to commonly held \softline
intuitions about justice, for instance that arbitrarily favoring some groups over others or violating \softline
basic rights is bad. If the neg wants to challenge those assumptions, s/he can, but requiring me to \softline
prove them ontologically true in a six-minute speech is absurd. Thus, there{\u8217\'92}s nothing wrong with \softline
me introducing asserted premises about justice into the round.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (4) MacIntyre ignores the fact that there are multiple kinds of truth. In particular, \softline
ontological truth of the sort ascribed to things like logic and math is distinct from the subjective \softline
truth of things like esthetic judgments. We accept subjective truths all the time{\u8211\'96}for instance, if I \softline
way {\u8220\'93}The Mona Lisa is a pretty painting,{\u8221\'94} we wouldn{\u8217\'92}t say that my claim is false because \softline
someone else might think it{\u8217\'92}s not pretty. Similarly, even if ethical claims just express subjective \softline
preference they can still be subjectively true for a given person if it follows from basic \softline
assumptions about justice that they personally accept. Thus, if I prove that eminent domain \softline
violates something that you see as a rule of justice, the resolution is true for you and you should \softline
affirm. This standard doesn{\u8217\'92}t greatly undermine the predictability of decisions since just about \softline
everyone agrees on some basic claims about justice, like the claims that slavery and genocide are \softline
bad.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (5) The aff isn{\u8217\'92}t necessarily bound to prove anything about justice. If I show that the \softline
takings process is structurally incapable of giving each their due regardless of what that is, that{\u8217\'92}s \softline
a purely factual claim and thus doesn{\u8217\'92}t bite into MacIntyre{\u8217\'92}s argument. [Show where you do this \softline
on the flow] Thus, even if it{\u8217\'92}s impossible for me to prove anything about the nature of justice I \softline
can still affirm.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
