}{\plain \fs24 \b 3. AT Ludwig Wittgenstein: {\u8220\'93}Ethics claims lack reference.{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (1) The card is blatantly unwarranted. Wittgenstein never actually proves that ethical \softline
claims can{\u8217\'92}t have reference; he just rants about a guy with a big book.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (2) Wittgenstein begs the question by assuming that a complete description of the world \softline
wouldn{\u8217\'92}t include any ethical truths. There{\u8217\'92}s no reason why the physical relationships between \softline
bodies necessarily has to be exhaustive of all the information in the universe.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (3) There is all sorts of information that we consider meaningful that wouldn{\u8217\'92}t be \softline
included in a complete description of the physical universe. For instance, I could know the \softline
positions of every physical body at every point in time and still not know the laws of physics that \softline
govern them. I would have to derive that from the information I had been given.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (4) Just as we can derive general physical laws from descriptions of the universe, we can \softline
derive normative propositions from our factual knowledge. For instance, a complete factual \softline
history of the Holocaust wouldn{\u8217\'92}t include any normative propositions, but we could derive an \softline
ethical judgement from the facts presented.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (5) Since we understand what is meant by ethical claims, they must have reference to \softline
something within our experience. For instance, some people argue that ethical claims refer to the \softline
phenomena of pleasure and pain. Since these phenomena are objectively real, they would have to \softline
be included in Wittgenstein{\u8217\'92}s book.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \b 4. AT Ludwig Wittgenstein: {\u8220\'93}Ethical claims rely on simile.{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (1) The claim that we can only express ethical claims through simile is ridiculous. If I say \softline
{\u8220\'93}Genocide is unjust,{\u8221\'94} that{\u8217\'92}s not a simile, but you still know what I mean. The resolution is also a \softline
normative claim, and there aren{\u8217\'92}t any similes in it either.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab (2) Even if there we could only express normative claims through simile, that would be a \softline
defect of our language, not of ethics. Since we intuitively understand what is meant by ethical \softline
claims, at least in terms of what behaviors they enjoin on us, ethical concepts can{\u8217\'92}t be empty. \softline
Lacking the language the express them properly doesn{\u8217\'92}t change that. [}{\plain \fs24 \i Wittgenstein was the one \softline
who wrote, {\u8220\'93}What can be shown cannot be said.{\u8221\'94}}{\plain \fs24 ]}{\plain \fs24 \b \par
