}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (1) The term {\u8220\'93}eminent domain{\u8221\'94} isn{\u8217\'92}t derived from US law. It comes from a treatise \softline
written by Dutch jurist Hugo Grotius in 1625, so the claim that it{\u8217\'92}s a US-specific term is absurd.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (2) Even if other countries use different terms for eminent domain, the power of eminent \softline
domain still exists. They don{\u8217\'92}t call chairs {\u8220\'93}chairs{\u8221\'94} in France, but there are still chairs in France.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (3) Even if other states don{\u8217\'92}t have precisely the same takings procedures, we can still \softline
analyze those associated with eminent domain in the abstract. We can debate whether the death \softline
penalty is unjust in a country that doesn{\u8217\'92}t have it, so even if the power of eminent domain didn{\u8217\'92}t \softline
exist in other countries that wouldn{\u8217\'92}t make the topic US-specific.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (4) Limiting the topic to the US harms learning since the range of research we can do is \softline
severely curtailed. Learning about the way takings work around the world is more educational \softline
than just learning how they work here. Learning matters since it{\u8217\'92}s the goal of debate and the \softline
reason schools fund it.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (5) Limiting the topic to the US violates framers{\u8217\'92} intent. If the wording committee had \softline
wanted us to just talk about the US, there{\u8217\'92}s no reason why they wouldn{\u8217\'92}t have put a clause in the \softline
topic making that explicit. Since the only way to assign objective meaning to ambiguous text is \softline
to look at what was meant by it, determining the meaning of the topic by this standard is the only \softline
way to make it debatable since otherwise its meaning would be perpetually indeterminate.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \b 2. AT {\u8220\'93}Topic not US-specific.{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (1) {\u8220\'93}Eminent domain{\u8221\'94} is a term of art coined in US law. Even if other states have \softline
equivalent powers, {\u8220\'93}eminent domain{\u8221\'94} thus refers to the particular legal powers of the US \softline
government to seize land. Thus, trying to discuss the topic internationally makes no sense.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (2) Equivalent legal powers of other states are significantly different. Australia, for \softline
example, doesn{\u8217\'92}t mandate just compensation for owners{}{\plain \fs24 \super 3{\footnote \pard \fs24\fi720 
{\plain \fs24 \super 3}{\par
}\pard \fs24
{\plain \fs24 }{\plain \fs20 \fs20 Wikipedia, {\u8220\'93}Eminent Domain,{\u8221\'94} 2005: {\u8220\'93}In Australia, s51(xxxi) of the Constitution permits the federal \softline
government to make laws with respect to "the acquisition of property on just terms from any State or person for any \softline
purpose in respect of which the Parliament has power to make laws". This has been construed to not necessarily \softline
mean just compensation as a just term might not of necessity be monetary or proprietary recompense.{\u8221\'94}}}}
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 . Thus, even if the term could apply to \softline
the legal powers of other states, it doesn{\u8217\'92}t.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (3) Discussing US eminent domain law has more educational relevance, since we live in \softline
the US.  Discussing US policy in more depth is thus more educational than attempting to discuss \softline
takings law around the world. Education matters since it{\u8217\'92}s the goal of debate and the reason \softline
schools fund it.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (4) Similarly, US takings law is more politically relevant since we actually have input on \softline
it through the democratic process and can do something about the discussions we have in round. \softline
Political relevance matters since the ability to understand and solve real-world problems will \softline
always outweigh purely hypothetical impacts.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (5) Limiting the topic to the US also allows fair and equitable division of ground, since if \softline
we have to debate several different sets of takings law there{\u8217\'92}s no way to determine which kind of \softline
takings the neg has to defend, precluding an objective evaluation of the round and mandating \softline
intervention. Fairness matters since debate{\u8217\'92}s a game and no one wants to play an unfair game.}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \b \par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \b 3. AT {\u8220\'93}{\u8216\'91}Use{\u8221\'94} means status quo.{\u8221\'94}\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (1) There{\u8217\'92}s a difference between the use of eminent domain and the specific way it{\u8217\'92}s used \softline
in a given context. Since the term {\u8220\'93}use{\u8221\'94} in the topic isn{\u8217\'92}t qualified, it makes most grammatical \softline
sense to talk about the use in general rather than specific uses.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (2) Limiting debate to the {\u8220\'93}status quo{\u8221\'94} is dumb since the way we set the limit has to be \softline
either arbitrary or so narrow as to preclude debate. If the {\u8220\'93}status quo{\u8221\'94} means what{\u8217\'92}s happening \softline
right now, then we can only talk about takings that are happening this second, absurdly limiting \softline
ground for research and debate. If we try to set a standard for how close to this instant something \softline
has to be to qualify as part of the {\u8220\'93}status quo,{\u8221\'94} there{\u8217\'92}s no objective way to do so; further, such an \softline
attempt violates the logic behind looking to the status quo in the first place, since it goes beyond \softline
present uses of eminent domain. Thus, debate shouldn{\u8217\'92}t be limited to the status quo.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \tab (3) Limiting debate to the status quo also harms learning, since it limits our ability both to \softline
research important historical aspects of the topic and to research broader philosophical arguments \softline
that attack or defend the use of eminent domain more generally. Learning matters since it{\u8217\'92}s the \softline
goal of debate and the reason schools fund it.}{\plain \fs24 \sa99 \b \par
